<subsection xml:id="subsec-Adding-proper-fractions">
    <title>Adding proper fractions</title>
    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Make a circular paper cut-out, divide it into 8 equal parts and shade or color it as shown below.
                </p>
                <image width="25%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="adding-proper-fraction-circular-image">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
                            \draw (-1,0) -- (1,0);

                            \fill[green] (0,0) -- (1,0) arc[start angle=360, end angle=270, radius=1cm] -- cycle;
                            \fill[green] (0,0) -- (0,1) arc[start angle=90, end angle=135, radius=1cm] -- cycle;
                            \node at (-0.3,0.6) {\large $a$};  
                            \node at (0.5,-0.5) {\large $b$};  
                            \draw (0,1) -- (0,-1);
                            \draw (-0.71,0.71) -- (0.71,-0.71);
                            \draw (-0.71,-0.71) -- (0.71,0.71);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What fraction of the whole circle do the colored parts <alert>a</alert> and <alert>b</alert> represent?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Combine together the two colored parts. Which fraction of the whole circle do the combined colored parts represent?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Add: <m>\frac{5}{6} + \frac{2}{7}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To add two proper fractions that have different denominators, we find LCM of denominators first. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, to find the LCM of <m>6\text{ and }7</m>, list multiples of <m>6</m> and <m>7</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Multiples of <m>6</m> are <m>6,12,18,24,30,36,{\color{red}42},48,54,...</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Multiples of <m>7</m> are <m>7,14,21,28,35,{\color{red}42},49,56,...</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                We can see that, the common multiple is <m>{\color{red}42}</m> and it is the least common multiple that we have.
            </p>
            <p>
                Hence, the LCM of <m>6\text{ and }7</m> is <m>{\color{red}42}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Rewrite the fractions as equivalent fractions using the LCM as the common denominator.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{5}{6} \amp = \frac{5 \times 7}{6 \times 7} = \frac{35}{42}</mrow>
                    <mrow></mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{2}{7} \amp = \frac{2 \times 6}{7 \times 6} = \frac{12}{42}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, since all the denominators are the same, we add the numerators and write the result as the final numerator on top of the common denominator.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{35}{42} + \frac{12}{42} \amp = \frac{47}{42} </mrow>
                    <mrow></mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{47}{42} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                finally convert the improper fraction to a mixed fraction.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{47}{42} \amp = 1 \frac{5}{42}</mrow>
                    <mrow></mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 1 \frac{5}{42} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
